properties.geogAndClimate: The Central Experimental Farm is located in the urban landscape of downtown Ottawa which is primarily underlain by bedrock. This particular site, however, was intentionally sought out for its rich soils. Harsh winters and humid summers are typical in this continental climatic region. Ottawa is located in the Great Lakes-St. Lawrence forest region which is dominated by unevenly aged hardwood forests as well as coniferous trees and deciduous broad-leaved species.
properties.integration: The Central Experimental Farm is located in the urban core of Ottawa.
properties.mainProducts: Crops: Wheat, Corn, Oats, Soybeans; Ornamental Garden: Heritage Roses, Lilacs, Peonies, Irises and Daylilies, Perennials; Arboretum: Magnolias, Crabapple Trees, Hostas, Shrubs
properties.operationScale: The Central Experimental Farm leads crop development from Manitoba to Prince Edward Island alongside other areas of research. Research at the CEF supports Canadian agriculture.
properties.cultivationSystem: n/a
properties.history: Located in the urban core of Canada’s capital city, the Central Experimental Farm was created in 1886 with the intention of creating profitable new agricultural methods agriculture in Canada. At its conception, it was designated as the central research station for the Department of Agriculture who selected the rectangular parcel of land due to its richness of soil types, access to rail transport, and proximity to land and water. The CEF is situated 3 kilometers away from Canada’s legislative core, Parliament Hill, which was built in 1859. The CEF continues to operate as a site of research and agricultural advancement as it was intended.
properties.heritage: The CEF, being situated in Canada’s capital city, has a variety of attributes which constitute its tangible and intangible heritage. Originally situated on the urban edge of Ottawa, the Central Experimental Farm is now situated well within the urban boundary. Having been able to retain its 19th century landscape, the CEF could be considered a setting of co-evolution, where it has developed in tandem with the city of Ottawa and been able to keep its tangible heritage intact. In terms of intangible heritage, its landscape is another important feature to consider, having been modeled after a English aesthetic movement which took place in the 18th century whereby theorists and practitioners attempted to model landscape after an idealized vision of nature (think: William Cronon’s “The Trouble with Wilderness”). This can be reflected in the open cultivated fields and their various sizes, colors, textures, and seasonal variations. These features serve as a window into the 19th century philosophy of agriculture. Another important component of the landscape, in reference to its function as a place of scientific advancements in agriculture, is its neatness and tidiness. In terms of living heritage, the CEF is now the headquarters to a national network of experimental farms and serves to address national agricultural issues that may arise. Past inventions at the CEF have included the frostresistant and early-maturing Marquis wheat, which has helped transform the Canadian Praries into one of the world’s strongest grain-producing areas. Current research activities at the farm are oriented towards enhancing environmental performance and establishing sustainable ways to develop field crop. Thus, the living heritage can be described as a co-evolution of the CEF with the scientific demands of the era.
properties.stakeholders: Ottawa Research and Development Centre, Department of Agriculture, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC).
properties.risks: n/a
properties.incentives: Currently, there are a variety of research activities which take place at the Central Experimental Farm which are aimed at enhancing environmental performance of agriculture.
sources: Central Experimental Farm National Historic Site of Canada. Canada’s Historic Places, https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=13811&pid=0. Accessed 21 July 2020.
Central Experimental Farm. Government of Canada, https://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/about-ourdepartment/offices-and-locations/central-experimental-farm/?id=1170701489551. Accessed 21 July 2020.

properties.geogAndClimate: Coastal hemlock forest, moderate oceanic climate
properties.integration: The UBC Farm is located on the University of British Columbia Vancouver campus. It is surrounded by residential buildings and school buildings.
properties.mainProducts: Fruits: Apple, blueberry, dandelion, strawberry, tomatillo; Vegetables: snap bean, dry bean, edamame bean, fava bean, romano bean, bulk beet, brunch beet, carrot, celery, celtuce, chard, collar, cucumber, fennel, flowers, squash, garlic, arugula, mizuna, mustard, scarlet frills, kale, kohlrabi, leek, lettuce, scallion, shallot, walla walla, pepper, potato, pumpkin, radicchio, radish, radish, salad mix, spinach, turnip, squash, zucchini; Herbs: basil, bay leaf, chive, cilantro, copper fennel, lavender, lovage, apple, peppermint, oregano, parsley, rosemary, sage, sorrel, winter, thyme
properties.operationScale: The UBC Farm sells produce via markets, wholesale distribution, online seed sales, and community supported agriculture (CSA) which exchanges the purchase of land shares for a weekly box of produce throughout the growing season.
properties.cultivationSystem: The UBC Farm is home to a small-scale, diversified, organic integrated production system. It contains cultivated annual crop fields, perennial hedgerows and orchards, pasture, teaching garden, and forest stands.
properties.history: One continuous aspect of the UBC Farm from the distant past to the present is its utilization as a place of agriculture and education. This site is located on the traditional, ancestral, and unceded territory of the Musqueam people who inhabited the land for thousands of years prior to documented history and used it as a place of inter-generational learning and teaching of culture, history, and traditions. Situated on what is now recognized as the Point Grey Campus of the University of British Columbia, the peninsula was long purposed as a training site for Musqueam youth. While the forest was used for hunting and gathering, the land itself was used as a place for education and growth. The thematic aspect of education can be reflected in the current state of the UBC Farm which is used as a place for teaching, learning, and research.
properties.heritage: The UBC Farm facilitates a sense of living heritage via the Indigenous Health Research and Education Garden (IHREG). The IHREG provides a context for the intergenerational education of intangible heritage features by connecting local Indigenous Elders and youth. Grounded in the principle that ‘food is medicine,’ the Medicine Collective, comprised of a group of Indigenous Elders and Knowledge-keepers who guide and direct activities at the IHREG, have grown the garden to include over 60 varieties of medicinal plants. The garden also engages with regional Aboriginal schools, communities, and organizations to facilitate the teaching and learning of traditional and non-traditional plant knowledge and a sense of living heritage.
properties.stakeholders: UBC; Centre for Sustainable Food Systems; Faculty of Land and Food Systems; Friends of the Farm
properties.risks: At a macro-scale, the UBC Farm is responding to challenges faced by global food systems such as population growth, global food demand, climate change impacts, and the global degradation of land. At a local scale, the UBC Farm’s main threat include development pressures, an aging farmer demographic, a lack of land availability for young farmers to utilize, and a preservation of diverse ecosystems and knowledge.
properties.incentives: Indigenous Food Sovereignty: with an end goal of food security, Indigenous food sovereignty is pertinent aspect of the IHREG. This aspect involves addressing the colonization of traditional regional food systems as well as land access and rights; Research: the UBC Farm provides open-access research and data including research data, operations/management data, and long term agroecological data gathered from research stations. The goal of making this data open-access is to encourage the dissemination of knowledge.

properties.geogAndClimate: Nanaimo is home to a temperate climate which include mild, rainy winters and warm, dry summers.
properties.integration: The Five Acre Farm is a discrete site located in a residential neighborhood of Nanaimo.
properties.mainProducts: Chickens, bees, fresh produce.
properties.operationScale: The Five Acres Farm ensured food security in its local region. The farm assists in skill development for community members of Vancouver Island University students.
properties.cultivationSystem: n/a
properties.history: Prior to European colonization, the area was known as Wakesiah by the local Snuneymuxw, which translates to “far away.” in 1863, Captain Horace Douglas Lascelles bought 9000 acres in the Wakesiah area and formed the Harewood Coal Company. In the early 1900s, the area was largely rural agricultural land. Development of the region began in the 1940s–by the second half of the century, very little farmland remained as urbanization swept the area. The Five Acres Farm is one of the last remaining historical five-acre lots alluding to Nanaimo’s unique mining heritage.
properties.heritage: The Five Acre Farm is a remnant of one of British Columbia’s earliest planned settlements. Elements of intangible heritage can be found at the farm including an acreage, house, barn, outbuildings, and orchards. These remnants stand in stark contrast to the area surrounding it, which have largely been developed into single family lots.
properties.stakeholders: Nanaimo Foodshare Society (NFS), Growing Opportunities Farm Community Coop (GOFC), and the Mount Arrowsmith Biosphere Region Research Institute (MABRRI).
properties.risks: The Five Acres Farm property faces risks of urban development.
properties.incentives: Food security; ecological sustainability and biodiversity through the preservation of wetland.
source: Five Acre Farm. Canada’s Historic Places, https://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/placelieu.aspx?id=3950&pid=0. Accessed 22 July 2020.

properties.size: 830 km² within a radius of 120km around St. Petersburg
properties.geogAndClimate: St. Petersburg is located in northwestern Russia, along the Neva River at the head of the Gulf of Finland. The city is located in lowlands and the delta of the Neva River; because the area has such low elevation, floods are common. Its climate is classified as a humid continental climate, meaning that it has warm and humid short summers and long, cold and wet winters.
properties.integration: Dachas are located in the suburbs of St. Petersburg, as they are meant to serve as escape from urban life. They are discrete plots of land with individual cottages located on them. They are typically located along train tracks or highways and are separated from the residential areas of the inner city.
properties.mainProducts: Vegetables: potatoes, carrots, beets, leafy salad greens; Fruits: redcurrants, gooseberries, raspberries, strawberries, apples, herbs; Exotic plants
properties.operationScale: Individual garden plots are organized in gardening cooperatives and associations. Each family has and operates one plot of land, which is typically around 600m2. Dachas gardens produce anywhere from 40%-50% of food consumed in Russia, using only 3% of farm land.
properties.cultivationSystem: Dacha gardens are an example of allotment gardens in which each family cultivates their own plot of vegetables and fruits that provide sustenance for the familty. Since the 1950s, there has been an increase in a community approach to the gardens that has allowed the gardens to connect to municipal electric and water networks. Most gardeners use hand tools, such as spades and spading forks, to cultivate and grow their crops. The crops are grown in separated beds that rest on the ground, separated by rows of gravel or earth.
properties.history: Dacha land plots originated in the 17th century, but they were mainly allotted to wealthy citizens who were in good standing with the Tsar. It was not until the 20th century that dachas were more widespread and that the lots were used for producing food, rather than as non-producing gardens. During the Soviet era, children were required to visit dachas to learn about agricultural production. In this time, dachas produced about 90% of the food that was consumed. The produce not only supplied the residents of the dachas but was also sold at market to feed others.
properties.heritage: Dachas have continued to evolve since their inception has ex-urban retreats for the wealthy. This evolution to allotment gardens has fostered a living heritage that continues to evolve as the needs and circumstances of contemporary people of St. Petersburg evolve. This nationwide phenomenon is in constant transformation. Additionally, the knowledge of self-sufficiency, fear of looming starvation, and lack of trust in mass-farmed produce continues to influence how farmers treat their plots. These cycles are an inherent Russian way of living.
properties.stakeholders: Private owners of each lot, as well as community and association members, are the key stakeholders.
properties.customers: Produce is consumed by the families that own the lots of land, while excess is stored and sold in urban areas.
properties.risks: Each plot has a different owner, so aside from the community-run plots, there are challenges in unifying owners from varying social classes along common goals of urban agricultural heritage.
properties.incentives: In 2003, Russia passed the Private Garden Plot Act that entitles Russian citizens to free, inheritable plots of land for gardening and growing crops.

properties.geogAndClimate: Minneapolis is seated at the intersection of the Minnesota River and the Mississippi River. The terrain is flat and rolling, and there are many lakes throughout the city. The city is located in the northern United States where there are large temperature variations between seasons.
properties.integration: The Dowling School Victory Garden is hosted on a discrete site in Minneapolis. During World War II, victory gardens were distributed throughout the city both in public lots and in residential yards. Throughout its history, the garden has moved throughout the city, but it has consistently been in one discrete location at a time.
properties.mainProducts: Vegetables: broccoli, cabbage, cucumbers, squash, melon, eggplant, lettuce, okra, peas, peppers, carrots, beets, onions, leeks, radishes, sunflowers, tomatoes; Flowers; Perennials
properties.operationScale: The scale has changed over time but has always been small. Victory gardens were established to fulfill local produce needs. Today, the produce from Dowling School Victory Garden is donated through local community groups, so the focus has continued to be on community sustenance.
properties.cultivationSystem: The soil that the gardens initially were in was quite rocky and was unfit for growing plants. They were moved during the war to a plot a few blocks over, that was owned by the University, to access and use better soil. Today, the site is irrigated from water pipes and water stations that run along the east side of both the north and south gardens. The garden plots were initially 50 feet by 120 feet, which was the size of a full city block. Today, 50 plots were subdivided from the initial 6. The gardens have grown to encompass surrounding gardens at Minnehana Park and now offer a total of 150 plots. There are 4 raised beds on the site that are designed for people to access in wheelchairs.
properties.history: The United States came to control this area of land in 1805 when it was taken from the native peoples from Zebulon Pike to establish a military fort, Fort Snelling. The land was surveyed and sold to white settlers. Part of the land, which would later become the Victory Garden, was designated as a marsh, and was determined to be unfit for cultivation. During World War II, the United States focused commercial food production on supplying the military troops. American citizens were asked to grow as much produce as they could on their own. At one point, these efforts, called Victory Gardens, supplied up to 40% of the fresh produce that the public consumed. After World War II ended, the funding for Victory Gardens also ceased, so many of them stopped functioning. This plot was part of the Dowling School for Crippled Children: the school building was built on part of the site, but the rest remained open. Fill was brought in to make the marshy area arable. In 1943, the open site was converted to a Victory Garden, as the Twin Cities (Minneapolis and St. Paul) established over 120,000 Victory Gardens. The gardens were moved twice during and after the war to seek better soil quality.
properties.heritage: After World War II, the plots continued to be farmed by individuals who took advantage of the public plots. Over time, the organization more from informal to formal, and today the plots are managed by a central group. The tangible heritage is the physical existence of the plots that have remained through today. The intangible heritage is the persistence of a type of urban agriculture that was formed out of a unique context that is directly tied to World War II.
properties.stakeholders: The garden is run by the Dowling Community Garden, which consists of volunteers who manage the land.
properties.customers: Produce is donated to community organizations.
properties.risks: The site does not have a consistent source of income and relies on donations and grants from outside sources.
properties.incentives: The Victory Garden has received an outside grant of $10,000, and receives annual dues from gardeners who rent their plots.
sources: Garden, Dowling Community. “Dowling Community Garden.” Dowling Community Garden - 2010, 2020, www.dowlingcommunitygarden.org.
Smetanka, Mary Jane. “Dowling Community Garden Marks Its 70th Year.” Star Tribune, 20 Aug. 2013, www.startribune.com/dowling-community-garden-marks-its-70th-year/220406711.

properties.geogAndClimate: Boston is a boggy and marshy coastal area. Even today, the gardens host many microclimates that vary from soggy and muddy areas to arable land.
properties.integration: The Fenway Victory Garden is hosted on a discrete site in Boston. During World War II, victory gardens were distributed throughout the city both in public lots and in residential yards. Today, Fenway is the only remaining victory garden in Boston and has expanded through the purchasing of other surrounding lots.
properties.mainProducts: Vegetables: tomatoes, salads, kale, lettuce, arugula, gourds, cucumbers, zucchini; Flowers; Herbs; Perennials
properties.operationScale: Fenway Gardens are part of Frederick Law Olmsted’s Emerald Necklace string of linear parks that run through Boston. It is composed of 500 garden plots that are rented out to members of the Fenway Garden Society. The Boston Food Bank receives excess produce.
properties.cultivationSystem: The 500 plots that remain today are rented out to individual gardeners who operate their plots as they choose. Initially after World War II, the plots were all used to grow flowers, but vegetables now occupy about 25% of the plots. Some gardeners are experimenting with vertical growing systems to make the most of their land.
properties.history: During World War II, the United States focused commercial food production on supplying the military troops. American citizens were asked to grow as much produce as they could on their own. At one point, these efforts, called Victory Gardens, supplied up to 40% of the fresh produce that the public consumed. After World War II ended, the funding for Victory Gardens also ceased, so many of them stopped functioning.
properties.heritage: Even when federal funding ceased, Fenway continued its operation. Fenway Victory Garden is the oldest continually operating Victory Garden in the United States. The gardens offer plots to Boston residents and partner with the Boston Food Bank to donate excess crops. The tangible heritage is the physical existence of the plots that have remained through today. The intangible heritage is the persistence of a type of urban agriculture that was formed out of a unique context that is directly tied to World War II.
properties.stakeholders: Today the gardens are managed by the Fenway Garden Society, which represents more than 475 gardeners who work the land. The additional parkland is owned by the Boston Parks and Recreation Department.
properties.customers: Surplus food is donated to the Greater Boston Food Bank to distribute to local soup kitchens.
properties.risks: Boston is a continuously growing city and a developer recently acquired an adjacent area of land to build a hotel across the street from the entrance to the garden. This threat was settled with a payment, but, as the city grows, similar threats could emerge in the future.
properties.incentives: The park is partnered with multiple departments within the City of Boston government, providing consistent financial support. Additionally, the farm partners with community organizations that provide additional funding and support.
sources: “History.” Fenway Victory Gardens, 8 Apr. 2019, fenwayvictorygardens.org/history.
Schons, Mary. “Fenway Victory Gardens.” National Geographic Society, 30 Nov. 2011, www.nationalgeographic.org/article/fenway-victory-gardens.

properties.geogAndClimate: Saanich is classified as warm and temperate. It is coastally located and experiences more rainfall in during the winter season.
properties.integration: Glamorgan Farm is located just north of Victoria International Airport.
properties.mainProducts: livestock, heirloom plants, vegetables
properties.operationScale: n/a
properties.cultivationSystem: n/a
properties.history: The Glamorgan Farm is one of the oldest farms on Vancouver Island that is still in use. It was installed in by William Booth in 1870, and then later run by Richard John and his four sons. The farm property was then subdivided, a portion of which was developed into a model farm in the beginning of the twentieth century.
properties.heritage: The Glamorgan Farm is an integral link between North Saanich and its rich agricultural history. Despite urbanizing pressures and growth, many elements of the farm property have stayed intact, including a cluster of agricultural buildings which constitute a farm compound, a two-story cross-shaped barn, a three-story hay barn, and other wood-framed agricultural buildings including smaller barns and a chicken coop. Thus, much of the heritage value is derived from the peculiar concentration of farm structures.
properties.stakeholders: City of North Saanich
properties.risks: n/a
properties.incentives: n/a

properties.geogAndClimate: Richmond has a warm and temperate climate. There is more rainfall during the winter than the summer.
properties.integration: London Heritage Farm is located by the Fraser River in a predominantly residential neighborhood.
properties.mainProducts: bushes, berries, herbs, annuals, perennials, bulbs, tree and vines
properties.operationScale: n/a
properties.cultivationSystem: Careful plantings are utilizes and natural predators permitted in order to prevent and control the spread of disease and pests. The growing season resembles that of an early English country garden which runs from early spring to early fall.
properties.history: The London Heritage Farm, associated with early pioneer settles Charles and William London on the South Arm, was likely constructed in two phases, with the norther area constructed in 1898 and the southern portion constructed in 1890. The London family constructed a ferry wharf in order to ship products which were cultivated at the farm. This resulted in growth and development of the South Arm region.
properties.heritage: Several of the pear trees found at the London Heritage Farm were planted at the beginning of the 20th century and are still actively producing fruit. Other remaining elements of the farm which constitute its heritage value include extensive gardens, landscape features, and outbuildings.
properties.stakeholders: The City of Richmond
properties.customers: Fruit are donated to the Richmond Fruit Tree Project who can or sell the fruit with proceeds or fruit going to the Richmond Food Bank.
properties.risks: The London Heritage Farm is located in an region where high tides and rises seas are a viable threat.
properties.incentives: n/a

properties.heritage: The brothers who managed the farm did not want any modern utilities such as electricity or plumbing, so the farm offers a glimpse back into the early days of Saanich.

properties.geogAndClimate: The Philippi Horticultural Area (PHA) has a cool coastal breeze which plays an important role in reducing the average climatic conditions of the area and facilitating greater crop production. The coastal breeze also allows for the cultivation of site specific crops. This area experiences harsh winds which pose a threat to crops if not dealt with effectively.
properties.integration: The PHA is located on the urban edge of Cape Town. It serves a buffer between the urban landscape and farmland.
properties.mainProducts: Cabbage, lettuce, cauliflower, broccoli, spinach, carrots, potatoes, onions
properties.operationScale: The Philippi market garden produces tons of vegetables and flowers for local consumption and supralocal export. The PHA is labor-intensive and is an important source of employment for communities in its vicinity.
properties.cultivationSystem: The PHA is described as a small scale with intensive farming practices. The intensive aspect of the PHA farming system pertains to the levels of production as well as the farming cycles which are enabled by the climatic and hydrologic conditions which are unique to the area.
properties.history: In 1656 the Philippi Area was regarded as a wasteland; plans to place a canal in the area were abandoned, and the land became regarded as ‘vacant government land’. In the 1800s and early 1900s, a series of grants were made to assist in the development of the PHA. In 1877, German immigrants were moved into the Philippi area. In 1883, a second round of immigrants, primarily poor farmers, day labourers, and woodworkers, were brought in from Germany. The PHA eventually grew into an important market garden which provided Cape Town residents with a variety of fresh vegetables into the 20th century In 2011, the City of Cape Town granted permission to developers to build a mixed use project called Oakland City where the PHA is located. In 2019, a coalition of farmers and activists took the government to court using a heritage argument to protect the PHA. In Febraury of 2020, using heritage documents written by the City of Cape Town, farmers and activists won the case.
properties.heritage: Intangible heritage: Philipi serves as a significant green backdrop and a distinctive border of the urban environment. Tangible heritage: The PHA is a remnant of the original landscape which was tilled by GermanSettlers in the 1870s. Moreover, the site is located in the ‘Coastal Dune Area’, which contains some of the last remaining intact dunes in the area. The dunes serve as a reminder of the physical barriers that were faced by early settlers.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: This area faces continuous development pressures despite its historic farming associations. Theft of infrastructure, equipment, and produce. Proliferation of informal dwellings and lack of public investment.
properties.incentives: The PHA has been described as a unique large green ‘lung’ situated in a dense urban environment. Provides employment for nearby communities which are afflicted with poverty and unemployment. The PHA still plays an important role in the City of Cape Town’s food network and the food security of the region.
sources: Battersby-Lennard, Jane, and Gareth Haysom. “Philippi Horticultural Area: A City Asset or Potential Development Node?” Rooftops Canada Foundation, 2012, www.afsun.org/wpcontent/uploads/2013/09/Philippi-Battersby-LennardandHaysom.pdf.

properties.geogAndClimate: Geneva is surrounded by 3 mountain chains and sits next to Lake Geneva, which is the source of the Rhone river.
properties.integration: Bude Farm is a discrete site located in the city of Geneva.
properties.mainProducts: Vegetables, Aromatics, Trees, Honey, Animals
properties.operationScale: Today, the farm seeks to engage urban dwellers to agriculture through renting plots, offering classes, and selling merchandise. Bude Farms employs people to work in the garden and at the market (paying a weekly wage), accepts community volunteers, and facilitates supply chains with other local producers to sell a wider array of products at the market.
properties.cultivationSystem: Bude Farms is an organic farm that uses permaculture principles. Because the site has such a small area, they employ “micro-market gardening” techniques, such as management of permanent planks, sowing and planting, composting, weed management with blackout tarps.
properties.history: Bude Farm was initially the land of the Bude Estate in Petit-Saconnex; the Bude family operated a working farm on their land and were officially absorbed by the city of Geneva in the 1930s. The site was initially 55 hectares up through the 1950s as Geneva expanded.
properties.heritage: The heritage value of Bude Farm derives mainly from its co-evolution with the surrounding city of Geneva. Despite urban transformations that took place in the 1960s and demolished much of the original farm, certain elements include the main vegetable garden from the 19th century still remains in use.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: Geneva has grown and, specifically during the 1950s and 1960s, has built more housing complexes. During this period, the Bude family sold their estate to the governance of Geneva and many of the buildings were torn down to build new housing. Even though this is in the past, the pressure for denser housing still exists. Additionally, Bude Farms has transitioned from selfsufficient farming to relying trade and sales due to the loss of productive buildings on the site. Bude Farms can no longer operate animal husbandry and other activities that required those buildings and now focuses on vegetable production.
properties.incentives: The canton of Geneva now owns the land that the farm operates on and uses this site as an “urban farm model” for new developments.
sources: Ferme de Budé: Urban and Organic Farming in Geneva. Cuisine Helvetica, https://cuisinehelvetica.com/2016/08/25/ferme-de-bude-urban-and-organic-farming-ingeneva/. Accessed 22 July 2020.
