properties.geogAndClimate: The Juckerfarm is based in the canton of Zurich. Zurich is considered to be a temperate climatic zone.
properties.integration: The Jucker Farm had three locations throughout the city of Zurich.
properties.mainProducts: Pumpkins, apples, pears, strawberries, raspberries, cherries, blueberries, asparagus, garlic, artichokes, kale, brussels sprouts, lettuce, rhubarb; Processed products: breads, bakery items, wine, beer
properties.operationScale: In addition to agricultural production, Jucker Farm is a considerable site for agrotourism. Jucker Farm employes roughly 150 people throughout all of it’s operations (including the three farms, farm shops, and restaurants).
properties.cultivationSystem: The farm is not certified organic, but applies many of the underlying principles. Grain is ground in their traditional stone mill, and then used for breads to sell in their restaurants and stores. They produce their own wine and similar alcoholic drinks.
properties.history: Jucker Farms operates three farms and the Jucker family has owned them for over a century.
properties.heritage: The heritage value of the Jucker Farm is mainly attributed to it’s impressive evolution with the urban infrastructure of Zurich.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: n/a
properties.incentives: Jucker Farms processes their food themselves and ensures a closed cycle to eliminate all food waste.
sources: Jucker Farm. Jucker Farm AG, https://www.juckerfarm.ch/. Accessed July 22 2020.
Jucker Farm. Wikipedia, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jucker_Farm. Accessed July 22 2020.

properties.geogAndClimate: Serra de Collserola is a mountain range between two rivers (Besos and Llobregat). Can Masdeu is located in valleys of those mountains.
properties.integration: Can Masdeu is a discrete site located in Collserola Park on the outskirts of Barcelona.
properties.mainProducts: Seasonal vegetables, potatoes, garlic, onions, tomatoes
properties.operationScale: Farmers use an organic growing system in 35 plots, a community garden, and orchards.
properties.cultivationSystem: Irrigation largely relies on rain water; the site employs water mines to gather water, ponds to hold excess water, and a tank to divert water when ponds are full. A water distribution system has been constructed to deliver water to all of the plots. Additionally, there is one well to access groundwater during the dry summer. Compost is made on site from plant waste, and manure is gathered from goats, sheep, and horses.
properties.history: Over time, the mountain range has been used for pastures, woods, vineyards, orchards, houses. In the 20th century, the land was over-used and and over-worked, leaving the hills degraded. This land was used to house a leper colony. When the hospital was vacated, the land was left empty and squatters moved in and have taken control of the area with the aim of revitalizing the agriculture that was once present in this area.
properties.heritage: The current efforts have revitalized the land to be used for cultivation again.
properties.stakeholders: Hospital de Saint Pau
properties.risks: Because this land is squatted upon illegally, there have been multiple eviction attempts. While the situation has cooled down and there have not been concrete steps to eviction since 2002, the threat still looms over those living and working the land.
properties.incentives: Can Masdeu partners with other organizations and groups in Nou Barris, the neighboring community, and participates in events to bring people together. While there is no specific economic incentive in place to ensure that Can Masdeu continues, the government has sided with Can Masdeu during eviction hearings and has designated the surrounding land as a Natural Park. Can Masdeu receives economic support from many outside organizations.
sources: Can Masdeu. Wikipedia, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Can_Masdeu. Accessed 22 July 2020. Community Gardens. Vall De Can Masdeu, https://www.canmasdeu.net/horts-comunitaris/. Accessed 22 July 2020.

properties.geogAndClimate: The Huerta region has a quintessential Mediterranean climate which consists of mild winters, very hot summers and rainfall concentrated in spring and fall.
properties.integration: La Huerta de Valencia effectively serves as a link between urban and rural regions in the outskirts of Valencia city.
properties.mainProducts: Oranges, vegetables, rice
properties.operationScale: 80% of the cultivated land area La Huerta de Valencia is used to produce fresh fruits and vegetables which is used for family consumption and also sold at commercialized markets.
properties.cultivationSystem: The irrigation system of La Huerta de Valencia has been integral in shaping its landscape, which is made up of cultivated fields, water channels, rural roads, barracks, and farmhouses. The Turia river has been a main source of irrigation since its conception as an agricultural system. Built during medieval times, a network of irrigation ditches extend and flow by gravity.
properties.history: The cultivation system of this region dates back centuries to the advent of Arab domination of the region which has played a role in shaping the agricultural landscape. The water management and distribution methods were implemented during the Muslim period and continue to be used today–this is evident through the measuring units which are used as well as the Egyptian elbow pattern which gauges the width of embankments.
properties.heritage: The co-evolution and persistent utilization of this agricultural landscape are prime factors in its heritage value. A sense of living heritage, alongside a strong tangible heritage in the form of an agricultural mosaic consisting of natural channels, fields, ditches, and rural roads, are important aspects of it’s value as an urban agricultural heritage system. Furthermore, the transmission of knowledge concerning water use and management from generation to generation is an important feature of its intangible heritage.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: Threats of speculation and development.
properties.incentives: The unique water-scape has provided water scarcity in the region which makes the cultivation of fruits and vegetables in the region possible.
sources: Historical Irrigation System at l’Horta de València. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, http://www.fao.org/giahs/giahsaroundtheworld/designated-sites/europeand-central-asia/historical-waterscape-of-lhorta-de-valencia/detailed-information/en/. Accessed 22 July 2020.
La Huerta de Valencia. What is it? Horta Viva, https://www.hortaviva.net/en/we-say/what-is-lahuerta/. Accessed 22 July 2020.

properties.mainProducts: violet artichoke, cardoons, green asparagus

properties.geogAndClimate: The climate in Aachen is warm and temperate.
properties.integration: Via Integration is a discrete site located in the outskirts of Aachen.
properties.mainProducts: tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, eggplants, salads, chard, pumpkins, kohlrabi, onions, beetroot, palm cabbage, radicchio, thai, cinnamon, red basil
properties.operationScale: Via Integration employs over 70 people with disabilities and is an important source of employment and training opportunities for people with and without impairments.
properties.cultivationSystem: Via Integration follows NATURLAND and BIOLAND guidelines in their growing process. The site entices wild animals through hosting insect holes, flower strips, nesting boxes, and dead wood piles.
properties.history: This site was initially developed in the Middle Ages as a pond and agricultural area. There is a pole marker on site that has signified the border between the Duchy of Limburg, the Duchy Julich, and the Kornelimunster Abbey. The land was disputed often and operated as a monastery and was later owned by nobles of low rank. The land was then passed down in the family for centuries. The land was comprised of a pond that served as a source of water for surrounding moats and ponds, in addition to fish farming and mill operation. The land was divided in the 20th century, and only a small portion of the compound was designated to remain as a source of agriculture. Since the farm changed structure and land, it employs handicapped people to work on the land.
properties.heritage: The heritage value of this farm is mainly attributed to the architectural preservation of the Gut Hebscheid which dates back to the 15th century.
properties.stakeholders: Via Integration belongs to the WABe eV-Diakonisches Netzwerk Aachen which supports people with special social difficulties.
properties.customers: Fruits and vegetables which are organically cultivated at the farm are sold at a variety of outlets on the site grounds as well as at several external markets.
properties.risks: n/a
properties.incentives: Via Integration works with the German Pension Insurance and with Rhineland Regional Association.
sources: Gut Hebscheid. Wikipedia, https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gut_Hebscheid. Accessed 22 July 2020.
Organic vegetable cultivation at the Hebscheid estate. VIA Integration gGmbH, https://www.viaaachen.de/de/. Accessed 22 July 2020.

properties.geogAndClimate: El Pilar lies in an ancient Maya city center along the border between Belize and Guatemala. The area is 12 kilometers from San Ignacio, Belize. El Pilar has an abundance of streams, which is rare in the area, and lies along the Belize River.
properties.integration: n/a
properties.mainProducts: chiles, corn, beans, squash, herbs, shrubs, trees
properties.cultivationSystem: El Pilar Forest Garden practices the ancient Mayan practice of a “milpa” system. This system consists of inter-cropping regional vegetables that are rotated with perennial shrubs and trees that reestablish the mature forest that naturally fills the area. This cycle takes 10 years: 2 years of cultivation, then the land is slashed and burned and lies fallow (while shrubs and trees grow back) for 8 years. This process is repeated indefinitely so that the land maintains its richness. Milpas traditionally plant crops two feet apart: a pole is used to poke holes in the grown after the old growth trees are burned. The farmer then steps in the hole to cover the seeds and leaves the plants alone for weeks. Large, permanent milpas can range from 2-10 acres. Semi-permanent milpas are grown around villages, but typically grow herbs and shrubs.
properties.history: El Pilar was initially a Mayan city, starting around 800 BC, but today is a historic archeology site. Remnants of small temples, palaces, plazas, housing, and access ways still exist today. Forest gardening existed around the village residential areas, similar to home gardens, to supply households with herbs. Larger plots were maintained to supply the city with food needs.
properties.heritage: While the ancient city of El Pilar is an archeology site today, the milpas influenced the urban design of El Pilar and continues to serves as a way for farmers to use traditional skills of forest gardening and supply food for the local community. Today, forest gardening is concentrated around the housing site. Contemporary Mayan farmers maintain, through knowledge passed down from generations, maintain the forest gardens based on the milpa system. This has yielded one of the most diverse ecosystems in the world: almost 90% of the plant life surrounding settlements can be used for food or household needs. The intangible heritage of the site is the milpa system of cycling through planting and lying fallow that has been passed down for centuries. While the ancient city of El Pilar is an archeology site today, the milpas influenced the urban design of El Pilar and continues to serves as a way for farmers to use traditional skills of forest gardening and supply food for the local community.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: The milpa system is most effective when feeding a small population. As the area around El Pilar has grown, milpas are unable to sustain the city’s population. Additionally, the site has been victim to looters and is considered to be endangered.
properties.incentives: The area is part of the El Pilar Archeological Reserve for Maya Flora and Fauna, so the land is protected and the focus of the protection is related to the milpas system. Part of the site falls in Guatemala, where it is also protected. A conservation effort, called Archeology Under the Canopy, is in place to maintain the site. Additionally, the El Pilar Forest Garden Network connects the Mayan farmers to each other and provides a platform to maintain cultural traditions, promote sustainable agriculture, and conserve the biodiversity of the Maya forest.

properties.location: West of and around the City of Granada, South Spain
properties.geogAndClimate: Summers in Granada are short and dry, while the winters are cold, long and cloudy. The Vega is located on Quaternary silts and alluvial soils which makes for productive cultivation and irrigation.
properties.integration: The Vega is spread across 40 municipalities. It forms an ecological corridor which connects Granada with other municipalities in the Guadalquivir Valley. It is divided by urban settlements.
properties.mainProducts: grains, fruits, vegetables, tobacco, olives and poplars
properties.operationScale: Most farmers have less than 5 hectares of land.
properties.cultivationSystem: Traditional cultivation techniques are based on water-ridges where the water runs through the fields.
properties.history: Large parts of the irrigation system were created in the 13th century, from there the Vega has grown throuout the centuries through small additions and is now getting reduced by urban growth. The man-made irrigation system designed in the Muslim-Era transformed the very dry land into fertile soil for agricultural production.
properties.heritage: The tangible heritage value of La Vega de Granada could be attached to its built irrigation network with its channels, dams, wells, reservoirs, and cisterns. Intangible heritage elements are related to its organization, water-distribution system, cultivation techniques, and specific fruits.
properties.stakeholders: Farmers, scientists, neighbours, politicians
properties.risks: Risks to the Vega include cutting of water supply due to urban growth and the replacement of sustainable agricultural practices with heavily industrialized commercial farming practices.
properties.incentives: Incentives to protect the Vega include an ecological and cultural heritage which has lasted 200 years and maintaining local food supplies.

properties.mainProducts: salad, radishes, cabbage, leek, carrots, onions, potatoes, artichokes

properties.site: Kuttanad Below Sea Level Farming System
properties.geogAndClimate: Kuttanad is The Kuttanad system has many geographic features including estuaries, flood plains, Kayals (i.e., shallow lagoons), ponds and canal networks. The climatic conditions are humid and tropical.
properties.integration: n/a
properties.mainProducts: Kuttanadan rice, Fin Fish, Shellfish, Freshwater Prawn, Clam, Shell Deposits, Duck, coconut, clay
properties.operationScale: Paddy cultivation in the Kuttanadan region constitues 25% of the total rice production in Kerala State. This system is considered to be the largest wetland use system in the west coast of the Indian Peninsula.
properties.cultivationSystem: The Kuttanad Wetland Agricultural System is the only paddy cultivation system in India which favors rice farming below sea level. The wetlands are created by the draining of delta swamps in bracking waters. The Kuttanad system consists of three main agriucltural landscapes which constitue a complex mosaic: wetlands which are used for rice farming and fish catching, garden lands dedicated to coconut farming, and water areas used for fishing and shells. Rice-fish rotation farming: double cropping of rice proved to be environmentally taxing and less lucrative, so a rice-fish roation farming system was implemented. November to February consists of rice cultivation and March to October consists of fish farming. This system produces good yields for fish and prawns, especially in fields less ridden with chemical fertilizers and pesticides. It also mitigates disease and pest problems related to rice farming and improves yields.
properties.history: The evolution of the Kuttanad Wetland Agricultural System to its current state can be explained through a series of reclamations beginning in the 19th century. Prior to the first reclamation, the land was vastly regarded as uncultivated government (sircar) wastlands. In 1818, the government issued a statement allowing for the reclamation and cultivation of these government lands. This was encouraged through a guarantee of possession for such lands with lighter taxes. The Pattom proclmation, issued in 1865, conferred land rights from the government to the tenants who were cultivating the land. The first reclamation was carried out by a group of entrepreneurs who functioned on a bartering system and engaged in a bilateral exchange of paddy. The extent of land reclamation during this period was approximately 250 hectares. The second phase of reclamation, where the government provided direct loans, began in 1888 and ended in 1903. This phase drew in many larger investments from influential farmers and resulted in a land reclamation of about 2000 hectares. The third phase lasted four decades, during which major fluctations of demand were experienced as a result of the first and second world war. With the advent of electric pumps in the region beginning in the 1940s and a decrease in dewatering costs, reclamation activities continues. During this phase, more than 5000 hectares of land were reclaimed.
properties.heritage: The co-evolution of the Kuttanad region and the unique paddy cultivation system is one aspect of its heritage value. Another aspect of its heritage would be its distinct uniqueness. It is the only below sea level cultivation system in India, and represents a creative and productive interplay between humans and the environment. Tangible heritage: The landscape of the Kuttanad farming system is an indicator of its tangible heritage value. It consists of an intricate, fragmented, complex, and multifunctional landscape which interwoven features such as riverts, marshes, ponds, garden lands, and networked water ways. Intangible heritage: The technique of below sea level cultivation, which has a strong likeness to the Dutch polder system, was developmed and mastered by Kuttanad farmers over 150 years ago. This system is valuable in that it bolsters the conservation of biodiversity and performs a variety of ecosystem services.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: Water scarcity: due to various factors such as pollution, urban enroachment, intensive agricultural runoff, untreated sewage from dense settlements, and land reclamation for agriculture and tourism, there is a severe shortage of potable water in the Kuttanad region. Nearly the whole region of Kuttanad is flood prone, which has become a greater issue in recent years. The increase in sea temperature may also have a negative effect of fish breeding. Overgrowth of invasive alien and native weedy species due to the stagnation of nutrients caused by fertilizers.
properties.incentives: Environmental services: water supply, health and sanitation, transportation, recreating and conservation of biodiversity, and regulation of hydrological system. The hydrological interplay between the Kuttanad cultivation system and the source of surface and ground water contributes to controlling flooding during monsoon and drought seasons in the summer.
sources: “Heritage Status to Kuttanad, Alappuzha, Kerala, India.” Kerala Tourism, 2020, www.keralatourism.org/kerala-article/2013/heritage-status-kuttanad/455.
M S Swaminathan Research Foundation, India and the Government of Kerala. “Kuttanad Below Sea Level Farming System.” UN FAO, 2012, www.fao.org/3/a-bp793e.pdf.
Thomas, P. M. “PROBLEMS AND PROSPECTS OF PADDY CULTIVATION IN KUTTANAD REGION.” Kerala Research Programme on Local Level Development, 2002, www.cds.ac.in/krpcds/report/thomascombi_doc.pdf.

properties.geogAndClimate: Mexico City lies along a series of lakes that are comprised of clear water, brackish water, and marshy wetlands. The area frequently floods and has high humidity. The chinampas are situated next to springs that line the southern shores of the lakes.
properties.integration: n/a
properties.mainProducts: Fodder crops, vegetables (salads), indigenous products (chia, maize, beans, squash), flowers
properties.operationScale: n/a
properties.cultivationSystem: Chinampas are connected to each other by a series of channels that serve as transportation and irrigation. They are about 1.5 meters deep. The soil remains fertilized through the flow of water and nutrients between the channels and the plots: the aquatic vegetation present in the channels provides organic inputs for the soil.
properties.history: The Aztecs took control over the region of what today is Mexico City through a series of military exercises. They expanded the area of the chinampas and created dikes to keep the water desalinated. The Aztecs built their capital, Tenochtitlan, on a constructed floating island in the lake. As the capital city grew, there was an increased demand for food, and the chinampas’s ability to produce food year round (in 5 growing cycles) was integral to feeding the empire.
properties.heritage: Today, many of the chinampas plots remain in use, yet many have become overgrown. Farmers still use canoes to access their plots, in addition to more modern transportation methods. The tangible heritage that remains active today is the physical plot of the chinampa, and the construction process of the floating islands serves as intangible heritage.
properties.stakeholders: Chinamperos, Government, Tourists, UNESCO
properties.risks: During the Spanish conquest of Mexico, Spaniards drained many of the lakes in Mexico City, which has limited the capacity of the chinampas. In addition to this limited water supply, climate change, urban sprawl, and water pollution threaten the existence of the chinampas. Farmers produce their crops at such a scale that enables wholesale, but other wholesale producers are able to offer lower prices.
properties.incentives: Incentives to continue operation and expansion today come from a social side. By operating the chinampas, farmers are able to connect to their history and the intangible heritage of the worldviews and connections between earth and people that was originally seen by those who created the chinampas. Additionally, tourism is a large economic driver of the area and brings tourists out on boats to ride through the channels on paid tours.
sources: http://www.fao.org/giahs/giahsaroundtheworld/designated-sites/latin-america-and-the-caribbean/chinampa-agriculture-in-the-world-natural-and-cultural-heritage-zone-in-xochimilco-tlahuac-and-milpa-alta/detailed-information/en/

properties.geogAndClimate: The land in Egypt is largely desert, with the exception of the land along the Nile River. The Nile River runs through the country and serves as a life-source. The arable land, due to the flooding of the Nile River, is fertile and rich with nutrients.
properties.integration: Due to the importance of the Nile as a cultural and environmental resource, most settlements in Egypt flank the Nile Delta and the Nile riverbanks. Urban agriculture has concentrated along the entrance to the Delta.
properties.mainProducts: Dairy (cow and buffalo), processed dairy (milk, butter, cheese, yogurt), Egyptian clover, cereals (wheat and maize), vegetables and green fodder
properties.operationScale: There are two main types of family urban farms in Cairo: integrated farms that practice polyculture and animal husbandry and landless farms devoted to milk production. Farms are primarily operated for family consumption, but surpluses are sold in very short supply chains. In Cairo, the sale of processed products is not very common, so the dairy is often sold as milk, and occasionally as cheese, butter, or yogurt.
properties.cultivationSystem: Family farms are often located on small plots about 2 feddans (.84 hectares) in area. Water management was previously centered on public irrigation channels and the main drainage network. Farmers were able to access water from the Nile for free, as Islam dictates free water. Now, due to a lack of funds for maintaining public irrigation channels, farmers use shared pumps to raise water from irrigation canals or wells. The greater focus is on water drainage due to the rise in the water table; water drains through a series of channels to prevent the plots from becoming saturated salt as the water evaporates but leaves behind salt.
properties.history: Egyptian agriculture dates back several millennia and is concentrated along the Nile River. Cows have held a sacred position in Egyptian culture as a symbol of fertility and maternity as far back at the 5th millennia BCE. Buffaloes were first introduced in Egypt in the 7th century. Because the Nile River has been the locus for human settlement and agricultural production, agriculture has been conducted in urban areas. Since the 1950s, there has been a greater push to extend agriculture into the desert to allow for more dense populations in urban areas.
properties.heritage: Cultural associations with cows and buffaloes have been pervasive throughout Egyptian history. Cheeses from cows and buffaloes have been documented since 2000 BCE and remain an important staple of the Egyptian diet. Intangible heritage focuses on specific Egyptian milk and cheese dishes that have been created over centuries, such as mish. Additional intangible heritage is the agricultural knowledge that is passed down orally over generations, from fathers to sons. Domestic knowledge on the processing of animal production and knowledge on the care taking of animals is passed down from mothers to daughters.
properties.stakeholders: Urban agriculture is often conducted at a family or extended family scale. “Family councils” make decisions regarding the strategy of the farms of the various extensions of the family; therefore, decisions are interdependent and part of large networks.
properties.customers: In urban Cairo, farmers sell their milk directly to milk shops or consumers. In peri-urban areas, farmers sell their milk to traders, and traders sell the milk to milk shops in urban areas. Excess milk remaining at milk shops are sold to milk processors.
properties.risks: Urbanization poses a risk to arable land, as more people move to Cairo to occupy the same footprint of land. Many farmers rent their land from public and non-profit owners for one-year lease terms, which yields uncertain futures for farmers. Pollution and urbanization both block irrigation and drainage channels; as the water table rises, the soil becomes saturated with saltwater and cannot drain, leading to salinization of the soil.
properties.incentives: National policy has focused on extending agricultural land into the desert to improve the productivity of existing farms and decrease international dependence for food products.
sources: Daburon A., Alary V., Ali A., El-Srogi M., Tourrand JF. (2018) Urban and Peri-Urban Agriculture, the Dairy Farms of Cairo, Egypt. In: Bosc PM., Sourisseau JM., Bonnal P., Gasselin P., Valette É., Bélières JF. (eds) Diversity of Family Farming Around the World. Springer, Dordrecht. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-024-1617-6_4

Daburon A., Alary V., Ali A., El Sorougy M., Tourrand J.F. (2017) Urban Farms Under Pressure: Cairo’s Dairy Producers, Egypt. In: Soulard CT., Perrin C., Valette E. (eds) Toward Sustainable Relations Between Agriculture and the City. Urban Agriculture. Springer, Cham. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-71037-2_5

Galal, Shazli & Alary, Veronique & Radwan, Mohamed & Abdelghany, S. & Corniaux, Christian. (2014). Urban and peri-urban milk development in Greater Cairo (Egypt) : What future for the traditional milk sector ?.

properties.geogAndClimate: Gonabad is located on the edge of a desert area and thus experiences an arid and semi-arid climate. A majority of the areas are plainlands.
properties.integration: A decent proportion of residential areas in Gonabad are farmlands.
properties.mainProducts: Saffron, cumin, wheat, barley, grape and almond; local textiles such as carpet and silk textile weaving; pottery
properties.operationScale: Saffron cultivation in Gonabad is primarily a locally oriented system of traditional farming. Cultivation is carried out for the livelihood of families, so industrial farming is not characteristic of this landscape.
properties.cultivationSystem: Qanats are the main source of water; an underground channel which transports water from an aquifer to a water well for drinking or surface for irrigation. There are 599 Qanats, 106 springs, and 294 deep and semi-deep wells supplementing water for agricultural and human use in this region.
properties.history: Compared to cereals, saffron cultivation is not water intensive. This resulted in more land being dedicated to farming saffron over time in the Khorasan province. Saffron cultivation was historically broader and less spatially concentrated. Today, 95% of saffron production takes place in the Khorasan province in northeastern Iran.
properties.heritage: Tangible heritage: The Qanat system which supplements the region with water has a history stemming back to the Aryan era, when many of the qanats were built. The oldest Qanat is the Qasabeh Qanat of Gonabad which is 33,133 meters long and dates back 3000 years. Intangible heritage: Qanats were used during the Achaemedian era (c. 625 BC) in Iran. The blueprint for the water management system was exported to other regions including Egypt, North Africa, Cyprus,and Sicily. During the Parthian period (205-2121 BC), many qanats were purposefully destroyed in an effort to resist Roman occupation. During the early Islamic period, Iranian scientists wrote about the principles of gravity and flow, illustrating that they had knowledge of underground waters. Vertical wells were slowly replaced by horizontal wells. Saffron is an important part of Iranian culture. Saffron farms were originally created in the ancient Median state of Alvand and the Zagros mountain range 4000 years ago. Iran has remained the largest producer of Saffron ever since. Production methods and techniques have been passed on through generations.
properties.stakeholders: Saffron production is important in keeping the local economy afloat. The trading of Saffron flowers and roots at Gonabad’s market constitutes a significant amount of economic activity and plays an important role in the presence of local festivities in the region.
properties.risks: Drought, climate change, sanctions
properties.incentives: Saffron cultivation has created local job opportunities which in turn has reduced emigration. The qanat water system has created a sustainable and efficient water consumption system and played a role in creating sustainable livelihoods. From a tourism point of view, the Gonabad region’s rich history of Saffron production is very valuable. Other landmarks such as the Saffron museum of Seno Village play a role in the touristic value as well. Farmers use Saffron leaves to feed livestock, adding to its economic importance. Saffron is a water efficient crop.
sources: “A Proposal for Designation as a GIAHS Qanat - Based Saffron Farming System in Gonabad.” UN FAO GIAHS, Dec. 2018, www.fao.org/3/CA3438EN/ca3438en.pdf.
“Iran’s Saffron Farming System Wins FAO World Heritage Status.” Tehran Times, 24 Dec. 2018, www.tehrantimes.com/news/431044/Iran-s-saffron-farming-system-wins-FAOworld-heritage-status.

properties.geogAndClimate: Jos Plateau is located in Nigeria’s Middle Belt and has a temperate climate that is well suited for the production of fruits and vegetables. The plateau is bounded by cliff faces and is made of three types of granite, one of which includes tin, which led to massive mining in the early 20th century from European powers.
properties.integration: Tin mining defined the colonial economy in Nigeria in the early 20th century. Mines were placed throughout the urban area of Jos. After the shuttering of the mines, urban agriculture has taken over the former mines and is integrated in the same manner as the mines. Furthermore, even before the closing of the mines, urban agriculture existed on a smaller scale elsewhere in the city during the period of colonialism. Agriculture has started spreading out from the city as well, so that farmers can access more land.
properties.mainProducts: tomatoes, greens (cabbage, lettuce, spinach), vegetables (celery, onions, green beans, peppers), roots and tubers
properties.operationScale: The agricultural production is focused on supplying markets in Southern Nigeria, as well as Niger and Chad. There is a complex supply chain, involving a number of intermediaries, that move the produce to market.
properties.cultivationSystem: Irrigation is conducted through small petrol-powered pumps that have become increasingly prevalent. Before the pumps, farmers relied on knowledge passed from rural farmers and hand operated shaduf to access water. After the tin mines closed, many areas of the mines were converted to ponds to hold water for the agricultural fields that evolved in other areas of the mine compounds. Now, the small pumps have allowed more and more land to be used for farming. Within the fields themselves, water flows through communal channels and then is drawn to flood individual beds. The fields are farmed year-round, without any fallow periods, which takes a toll on the soil quality. Fields employ intercropping to grow multiple species of vegetables in the same plot; this reduces the risk of disease or pests wiping out entire swaths of crops.
properties.history: In the early 20th century, there was European presence in the region due to extensive tin mining. During this time, urban agriculture began. In the 1970s, urban agriculture took up a greater market presence as tin production declined. This period, also characterized by an oil boom, freed up the land from tin production and led to a reclamation of the mines to be used for agriculture. Market gardening provided food for the expanding urban population. Following the crash of oil production and a national import ban on food products, the urban agriculture sector continued to expand.
properties.heritage: The growth of urban agriculture in the late 21st century has led to an economic growth of the people of the area. Nigeria, with its oil deposits, should be a wealthy Sub-Saharan country, but mismanagement, corruption, and military rule have wrought havoc on the country and the people. The expansion of vegetable production in Jos has been viewed as a remarkable achievement. The tangible heritage is the land conversion from tin mines to ponds that now hold water for farmers, as well as other areas of the mine for hosting fields of agricultural production.
properties.stakeholders: Farmers, traders, and other intermediaries form a complex network. Agriculture has attracted Fulani migrants to move to the city for work; this immigration stokes the flames of racial and ethnic tension that has already existed among the Berom and earlier immigrants, Hausa.
properties.customers: Vegetables are sold to markets in South Nigeria, Niger, and Chad.
properties.risks: Traders, often behaving as a cartels, that move the produce to different markets in the region have engaged in exploitative behavior toward the urban farmers. Due to the year-round production cycle, farmers deplete the soil without affordable access to fertilizer. Pests and diseases are a growing problem. Additionally, many farmers are not educated on farming practices or on environmental risks.
properties.incentives: The Plateau Agriculture Development Programme works to provide affordable fertilizer to farmers.
properties.sources: Porter, Gina, et al. “Markets, Ethnicity and Environment in a Vulnerable Landscape: The Case of Small-Scale Vegetable Production on the Jos Plateau, Nigeria, 1991-2001.” The Geographical Journal, vol. 169, no. 4, 2003, pp. 370–381. JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/3451575. Accessed 22 July 2020.

properties.geogAndClimate: Addis Ababa lies at the center of Ethiopia. The northern and central parts of the city are defined by rugged topography, while the southern portion is undulating. Rivers run through the city, creating valleys that are not suitable for construction, but allow for urban agriculture. The climate is warm year-round in Addis Ababa, and is labeled as “subtropical highland.” The area experiences a rainy season that coincides with summer, but drastically reduces the temperature, providing winter-like temperatures.
properties.integration: The municipality of Addis Ababa owns all land that is not strictly privately owned. Valleys along rivers are not suitable for private construction, so much of this land has been converted to urban farming. The most extensively used river valley for urban agriculture is Little Akaki. The Mekanisa-Gofa-Lafto farm is located along the Little Akaki River and is one of the oldest operating co-operative farms. These farms have not spread beyond the valley, but rather take up unoccupiable urban land.
properties.mainProducts: Cows, chickens, vegetables (swiss chard, kale, cauliflower, lettuce, leek, cabbage), legumes, roots and tubers, eucalyptus, medicinal herbs
properties.operationScale: There are around 250 farmers that operate plots in the Little Akaki River valleys. About 80% of the crops produces are sold at market, and crop sales account for an average of 60% of income for families.
properties.cultivationSystem: Plot sizes vary from less than 500 m2 to over 3,000 m2. All plots employ furrow irrigation. Farmers cannot afford pumps to carry water through their fields, so they use basin irrigation, which consists of dams built along the Little Akaki River that then transfer the water to the fields through channels. Each farmer opens a hole in the channel to allow water into their fields. The water is able to flow through the fields due to the pull of gravity. Up-river plots are able to receive water more than down-river plots. The plots are farmed 9 months of the year, with a break during the rainy season. This constant farming depletes the nutrients of the soil, so farmers use inorganic fertilizer purchased from the Ministry of Agriculture.
properties.history: Urban agriculture has shaped Addis Ababa since its creation at the end of the 19th century. Addis Ababa was established by Emperor Melenik at the geographical center of Ethiopia. The city developed along three nodes: a political center, a church, and a market. The growth of Addis Ababa has been characterized by periods of sporadic growth; since its founding in the late 19th century, the city has grown to 540 square kilometers. When Italy controlled the country in the 1930s, the ruling Italians established vegetable production and hired many locals to work the land. After Italy left Ethiopia in 1941, the land transferred to those migrants who had been working it for the Italians.
properties.heritage: Many of the city’s earliest residents engaged in urban agriculture, and urban agriculture has continued since. The intangible heritage of the knowledge and farming techniques is similar to that of the farming practices in rural areas of Ethiopia because many of the urban farmers are descendants of the Gurage rural farmers. Micro-dams for irrigation in the Little Akaki River are items of tangible heritage: some were constructed as long ago as the Italian occupation in the 1930s. These micro-dams, and the corresponding basin irrigation, are a method unique to Addis Ababa and the Little Akaki River.
properties.stakeholders: Most of the farmers, about 88%, who work the land at the Mekanisa-Gofa-Lafto farm are of Gurage descent, and most have immigrated to the area over the past few generations. Many of the farmers also employ day laborers who work in the fields. The Ethiopian government is engaged through both the Ministry of Agriculture that sells fertilizer to farmers and at a municipal level by allowing farmers to work on the public land. Additionally, the government recently established the Addis Ababa Urban Agriculture Office, which has the goal of supporting urban and peri-urban agriculture.
properties.customers: Farmers sell their produce to the Wholesale Vegetable Market in Mercato (Atakilt Berenda), which is run by the Urban Producers Association.
properties.risks: Farmers cannot access credit from formal financial institutions because the farmers cannot use their land as collateral. Instead, farmers obtain credit from wholesalers in the form of advanced payment. Additionally, farmers face the following risks: fear of losing their land, high prices for seeds and fertilizer, shortage of irrigation water, contamination of irrigation water, inadequate land for cultivation, lack of adequate equipment, pests and diseases, pollution, and theft.
properties.incentives: The Addis Ababa Urban Agriculture Office has been established to assist farmers, but farmers have not seen much benefit. Additionally, Addis Ababa has signed onto the declaration “Feeding Cities of Northern Africa” that promotes urban agriculture.
sources: Kebbede, Girma. “Farmers in the City: The Case of Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.” Academia, 2011. Mount Holyoke College, www.mtholyoke.edu/sites/default/files/acad/geography/docs/FarmersinAddisAbaba.pdf.

Gebremichael, D., Gebremichael, A.T., Worku, A., Abshare, M.W., Habtemariam, Y.M., Balcha, G. and Gebremichael, D. (2014). Building Urban Resilience: Assessing Urban and Periurban Agriculture in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. [Padgham, J. and J. Jabbour (eds.)]. United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), Nairobi, Kenya.

properties.geogAndClimate: The OZCF is located in the foothills of Table Mountain in Cape Town. This region specifically is one of the most biodiverse in the world–the Table Valley in Cape Town has an estimated 2200 species of plants, which is more species than the entirety of the United Kingdom. It has a warm Mediterranean climate which includes mild and moderately wet winters with dry and warm summers.
properties.integration: The OZCF is located in an affluent suburb in Cape Town.
properties.mainProducts: vegetables, fruit, herbs, seeds, seedlings, plants, fertilisers
properties.operationScale: Produce grown at the farm is sold at the OZCF Market on a weekly basis.
properties.cultivationSystem: n/a
properties.history: The OZCF has a known history which dates back to 1709. The farm was occupied by the Van Breda family for 7 generations who continuously grew their land holdings and operation until their estate occupied the largest part of the Table Valley. During the peak period of its production, the Van Breda family had employed 40 slaves who were instrumental in the prosperity of the farm which fostered most of its wealth from the production of fruit and vegetables. Water supplied from the springs of Table mountain, which had been used by the indigenous San and Khoekhoe peoples prior to European colonization, allowed for the OZCF to thrive. As the water was diverted to support the growing city the farm witnessed a decline in productivity. In 1901, the land was sold to a syndicate which established a suburb on the former farmland. The Oranjezicht farmstead remained intact until 1955 when it was abolished and replaced with a bowling green. Eventually, the bowling green was neglected and the area which was home to the former farmstead saw an accumulation of rubble as well as an increase in drug related activities. In 2009, the Oranjezicht-Higgovale Neighborhood Watch started organizing clean-ups in order to improve the welfare of the site. In 2012, the bowling green was transformed into the Oranjezicht City Farm.
properties.heritage: Tangible heritage: The OZCF is situated where the Oranjezicht farmstead once stood. It currently constitutes a portion of the original farmland. Having gone through a period over a century long where it no longer pertained to agriculture, the land has now returned to a state where it fosters farming activities.
properties.stakeholders: South Africa Urban Food & Farming Trust (SAUFF): The OZCF is part of the SAUFF, a nonprofit public benefit organization which supports collaborative urban agriculture initiatives, social farms and markets, in order to strengthen community social cohesion, improve food security, conserve natural urban ecosystems, and strengthen collective agency within communities. Friends of the Farm: A club centered around the OZCF and other urban agriculture initiatives. Friends of the Farm conduct activities related to raising awareness, fund-raising, and educational projects.
properties.customers: Produce from the OZCF is sold at a weekly market in Cape Town.
properties.risks: No risks mentioned specific to this site.
properties.incentives: Bokashi: The OZCF has a drop-off station for household food waste which then undergoes a process known as bokashi composting where food waste is fermented into a safe soil-enriching builder and used to grow fresh vegetables.
sources: “Bokashi Brigade.” Oranjezicht City Farm, 7 May 2020, ozcf.co.za/volunteer/bokashi-brigade.
“The Early Cape Slave Trade.” South African History Online, 27 Aug. 2019, www.sahistory.org.za/article/early-cape-slave-trade.

properties.size: 217.5 km² (Total wetland area in Greater Harare)
properties.geogAndClimate: The climate in Harare is wet and temperate.
properties.integration: n/a
properties.mainProducts: vegetable, maize, rice
properties.operationScale: In Harare, vleis are used in small-scale cultivation. Outside of the city, they are used on a larger scale.
properties.cultivationSystem: Vleis emerge in water logged drainage systems in clay and sandy soils. They occur seasonally during the wet season, from October to March. Vleis expand during the wet season and contract in the dry season. During this time, drainage systems transform into surface marshes. People utilize these marshes to plan an early crop and a late crop.
properties.history: Vleis have been used since before European colonization in Zimbabwe. They are an environmental occurrence unique to Zimbabwe.
properties.heritage: n/a
properties.stakeholders: Conservation Society of Monavale (COSMO), Aage V. Jensen Charity Foundation (AVJCF), BirdLife Zimbabwe
properties.risks: Cultivation on vleis is currently prohibited in order to preserve them. However, this legislation is not regularly enforced.
properties.incentives: n/a
sources: Mbiba, B. Urban Agriculture in Harare: Between Suspicion and Repression.
Kutiwa, S., Boon, E., and Devuyst, D. (2010). Urban Agriculture in Low Income Households of Harare: An Adaptive Response to Economic Crisis. Journal of Human Ecology, Vol. 32(2), 85-96.

Drakakis-Smith, D., Bowyer-Bower, T., Tevera, D. (1995). Urban poverty and urban agriculture: An overview of the linkages in Harare. Habitat International, Vol 19(2), https://doi.org/10.1016/0197-3975(94)00065-A.

properties.geogAndClimate: Cape Town is one of the ost bio-diverse regions in the world, containing 19 vegetation types, some of which are unique to Cape Town. It has a warm Mediterranean climate which entails mild and moderately wet winters with dry and warm summers.
properties.integration: The VOC Vegetable Garden is a discrete site located at the Company’s Garden park and heritage site in the urban core of Cape Town.
properties.mainProducts: celery, radishes, onions, leeks, cabbages, lettuce and peas, blueberries, strawberries, gooseberries, raspberries, peach, plum, apple, pear, quince citrus trees, rose geranium, buchu, lavender
properties.operationScale: The garden is located in the Company’s Garden which is a well-known greenspace in Cape Town. The produce from the garden is sold at a local farmer’s market held on Saturdays, and the vegetables are used at the Company’s Garden restaurant. Otherwise, the garden is used as a place of education for school children to learn urban food farming techniques throughout the year.
properties.cultivationSystem: Most of the watering is done using hosepipes. Some water is provided via flood irrigation through Dutch “leiwater” or water channels.
properties.history: The Vereenigde Oost-Indische Compagnie (VOC) Vegetable Garden’s history dates back to 1652, when Dutch merchant settlers had decided to set up a refreshment station, including a vegetable garden, in the area. Many sailors at the time were dying of scurvy during their long voyages, so the vegetable garden was implemented to provide sailors with the Vitamin C they needed to improve. Hendrik Boom, a Master Gardener in Holland, was tasked with the duty of constructing a nutritional garden in the area. Eventually, the old garden was displaced by development. In 2001, the City of Cape Town’s City Parks Department and Environment & Heritage Management Branch began drafting the project to restore the vegetable garden. In 2014, the VOC Vegetable Garden was constructed on the site of an old conservatory and parking lot.
properties.heritage: The Dutch Garden’s construction was based on historical maps, drawings, paintings, and town plans which reference the original garden. The design is consequently a stark depiction of the original seventeenth century Dutch Baroque layout, including stone-lined open irrigation channels. The irrigation system is likewise based on the original system designed by Jan van Riebeeck, a colonial administrator and Commander of the Cape from 1652 to 1662. There is an endangered medicinal herb section in the garden which serves as a reminder of the local knowledge which the San (i.e., indigenous hunter-gatherer inhabitants of South Africa) and Khoi (i.e., nomadic pastoralist indigenous population of South Africa) peoples once shared with new arrivals to the region.
properties.stakeholders: Company’s Garden: A park, heritage site, and tourist attraction in central Cape Town. The Company’s Garden was established by European settlers in the seventeenth century and maintains a variety of features today including a rose garden, historical statues, a restaurant, and a fish pond.
properties.risks: No risks mentioned specific to this site.
properties.incentives: The VOC Vegetable Garden is used as a place of education for school children to learn farming techniques which mitigates the disconnect between resource extraction and consumption.
sources: Sabi. (2016). Cape Town's Company Garden's Dutch Garden Historical and Futuristic. http://www.urbanlandscape.co.za/pdf-files/sabi-dutch-garden-historical-and-futuristic.pdf

Food24. (2015). Vegetables from the Company Garden’s: returning to Cape Town’s food garden roots. https://www.food24.com/vegetables-from-the-company-gardens-returning-to-cape-towns-food-garden-roots/.

properties.geogAndClimate: Hanoi is the capital of Vietnam, located in the north of the country, only 300 km below the Chinese border and 150 km from the ocean order.
properties.integration: Sites exist both in the urban area of Hanoi and on the edges of urban areas that are increasingly swallowed by the city.
properties.mainProducts: vegetables, rice, maize, sweet potatoes, flowers, trees, pigs
properties.operationScale: n/a
properties.cultivationSystem: As past of the Doi Moi reforms, each farming family received one plot of land. Farmers now use that their land according to how they choose to, and their decisions are influenced by the market. Irrigation is a challenging issue, as much of the water for irrigation is polluted. This has led to the labeling of “safe” crops that are grown with clean water.
properties.history: Hanoi is one of the oldest cities in southeast Asia and has existed for over 1000 years. The city has been under the control of many different dynasties and rulers from China, Vietnam, and France. During the American War in the 1970s, farmers were required to grow food for the war effort. Farmers worked collective farms and were told exactly what to grow. Doi Moi reforms allowed farmers to grow whatever they choose on their own plots.
properties.heritage: As part of the Doi Moi reforms, Vietnam opened more to the world, and residents’ tastes expanded as a result. Farmers have been able to accommodate new products through new-found freedom of choice. This is seen through a decrease in rice production and an increase in the production of fruit trees and animal husbandry. The intangible heritage is the plot allocation granted to every family during Doi Moi.
properties.stakeholders: Many farmers operate through cooperatives; during the 1980s, it was required that farmers work through cooperatives, but now they have the freedom to work independently. Farmers today have the freedom to purchase their own inputs and take their products directly to market.
properties.customers: Customers are concentrated in Hanoi and demand more expensive and exotic crops. As Vietnam has opened up its economy, the customers have more disposable income.
properties.risks: As Hanoi continues to expand, there is increased pressure on the farmers for their land. Many have shifted production from staple crops to vegetables, flowers, and trees because they earn merit higher prices at markets. As the city grows, land that produces higher earning crops will fetch a higher price at sale.
properties.incentives: The government currently encourages (via subsidies) farmers to grow “safe” vegetables from clean water.
sources: Lee, B., Binns, T., and Dixon, A. (2010). The Dynamics of Urban Agriculture in Hanoi, Vietnam. The Journal of Field Actions.
Pulliat, G. (2015). Food securitization and urban agriculture in Hanoi (Vietnam). https://doi.org/10.4000/articulo.2845

properties.geogAndClimate: Wanmu orchard has many geographic features, including delta flood plains, wetland, ponds and canal networks The climatic conditions are humid and subtropical.
properties.integration: n/a
properties.mainProducts: Lychee, Longan, Star fruit, Yellow peel, Banana, Mango, Guava, Papaya
properties.operationScale: The orchards were expropriated by the government as a national wetland park in 2015. Although some of the trees are still there, it is no longer a business type of agriculture.
properties.cultivationSystem: Wanmu orchard is a dike-pond system which is a traditional way for low-lying areas in flood plains in China to favor fruits and farm fish. The dike-pond system is created by digging the low-lying land into ponds and raising the surrounding land with soil excavated from the ponds to make a dike. The system consists of 2 main agricultural landscapes: ponds which are used for fish farming, dike areas used for fruit trees planting. In the circle of the system, the fruit tree is the first trophic level. Its leaves are food for wild birds and fish. The aquatic organisms in the pond work as reduction agents that decompose the organic matter in the pond like fish excreta and algae, and produce nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium in return. These elements are then returned to the dike when pond mud is used as fertilizer (Gongfu,1982: 191-202). This system can not only protect fruit trees from floods during tropical monsoon by draining surplus water, and also builds a productive ‘closed loop’ for the transfer of energy and exchange of substances.
properties.history: The evolution of Wanmu orchard to its current state can be explained through a series of phases.</br>The urban orchards, are actually transformed from the semi-natural, rural ancient orchard whose history can be traced back to 2000 years ago. During a long time, Wanmu orchard has been far away from the central city and famous for planting lychee(Litchi chinensis), composed by crisscross river network, dense fruit forests and some simple farmhouses, showing a peaceful and fertile picture of rural landscape.</br>Due to the rapid expansion of city center since the 1980s, Wanmu orchard has undergone changes in many aspects, as affecting its size, functions, and landscape patterns. Urbanization has transformed Wanmu orchard from a rural traditional agricultural system first into an urban agricultural park in the end of 1990s and then into a national wetland park in 2015. The orchard’s extent decreased massively from 40km2 in the 1980s to 11km2 left today. </br>And large parts of the traditional agricultural structure were transformed since the orchard have become a national wetland park. Moreover, the set of ecosystem services that are provided by the area has decreased, because Wanmu orchard lost its productive services and inherited cultural services and now is oriented only towards water purification and leisure functions for urban residents.
properties.heritage: The Dike-Pond system that was inherited from the 17th century, is most distinctive feature of Wanmu Orchard and it is also an indicator of its tangible heritage value. Dike-Pond system, one kind of polder landscape, is traditional integrated agriculture -aquaculture systems located in the riverine plains and estuaries of East and South China. The mosaic agricultural landscape composed of lakes, rivers and semi-natural fruit forest.
properties.stakeholders: Government and local farmers;</br>Government: The landowner, and set up Wetlands Management office which is responsible for the daily management of the entire park;</br>Local famers: People who have lost their land, but if they want, can become the daily managers of the fruit trees in the park and be paid by the office.
properties.risks: Before becoming a national wetland orchard, its risks mainly came from two aspects. On the one hand, its threat comes from external urbanization. Orchards are constantly being invaded by urban construction and the area is constantly shrinking. On the other hand, fruit trees are aging and yields are low. What's worse is that as the surrounding areas become part of the city, farmers tend to build more houses through illegal construction to rent out more houses to people who work in the surrounding areas, and gradually abandon farming.</br>After becoming a wetland park, although the area of the orchard is no longer shrinking, its base pond structure with regional characteristics gradually collapses and becomes an ordinary artificial wetland park.
properties.incentives: In order to further maintain this green space in Guangzhou’s high-density urban environment, since 2012 the local government has taken custody of the orchard’s remaining areas of about 8km2 by expropriating the owners – mainly farmers.
sources: Zhong, G. The mulberry dike-fish pond complex: A Chinese ecosystem of land-water interaction on the Pearl River Delta. Human Ecology 10.2(1982):191-202.

properties.geogAndClimate: Sao Luis Island is in the northern part of Maranhao, a state in Northeast Brazil. The island is a regional segment of the Brazilian coast in the Maranhense Gulf, which creates a large estuary system. Sao Luis lies between Sao Jose Bay to the east and Sao Marcos Bay on the west. The climatic conditions of the city are tropical, hosting an annual rainy season, but are suitable for growing vegetables, fruits, and other crops.
properties.mainProducts: papaya, cassava, bananas, coconut, passion fruit, beans, tomatoe, onions, roselle, green onions, coriander, gherkin
properties.operationScale: Homegardens traditionally consist of fruit trees grown around houses for the purpose of domestic consumption. At a commercial level, these plots are expanded into larger lots. Even though homegardens are small, they constitute much of the urban green space.
properties.cultivationSystem: Homegardens combine native trees with non-native trees, typically introduced during colonization, in yards to grow fruit, medicinal plants, and other trees. Homegardens are present in urban areas throughout Amazonia and present-day Brazil; yet, the defining feature of the homegardens in Sao Luis is that they have maintained a strongly native plant make up. As a result of the predominance of native species, the homegardens have a vertical structure, with three general zones: a lower stratum of fruit trees and saplings, a middle stratum, and an upper stratum of fruit trees and timber trees.. The structure reflects the degree of specialization and complexity.
properties.history: Homegardens are the oldest managed land-use system, often referred to as agroforestry, and serve as an important niche for fruit trees. Fruit trees were some of the earliest sources of agricultural harvesting for humans. Through time as urban areas grew and as outside powers interfered and started colonies, non-native species were introduced and tended to drive out native fruit trees, thus decreasing the biodiversity of the area. However, Sao Luis has maintained excellent standards of biodiversity and created a unique richness of native species.
properties.heritage: Sao Luis is comprised of rural centers that combine to create a peri-urban area. Agriculture occurs in the peri-urban space, while the commercialization of the agriculture occurs in intra-urban areas through street-market vending. Homegardens provide owners with means of subsistence and create important habitats for native fauna. The intangible heritage that is passed down is the biodiversity of the region and the native species that still flourish in urban areas. This heritage is still active today as farmers actively experiment with new plant species and new methods of cultivation.
properties.stakeholders: n/a
properties.risks: Some of the challenges that farmers in Sao Luis are facing relate to the access to physical markets: the conditions of roads are debilitating during the rainy season and many farmers do not have access to vehicles.
properties.incentives: There is increasing support for maintaining biodiversity in home gardens.
sources: Gomes, João Flávio B, Gomes, Renata SB and Souza, Alex OThe multifunctionality of urban horticulture and its integration with the city ecosystem: a brief review of concepts and the case of São Luís. Horticultura Brasileira [online]. 2019, v. 37, n. 3 [Accessed 7 August 2021] , pp. 252-259. Available from: <https://doi.org/10.1590/S0102-053620190301>. Epub 07 Nov 2019. ISSN 1806-9991. https://doi.org/10.1590/S0102-053620190301.

Akinnifesi, F.K., Sileshi, G.W., Ajayi, O.C. et al. Biodiversity of the urban homegardens of São Luís city, Northeastern Brazil. Urban Ecosyst 13, 129–146 (2010). https://doi.org/10.1007/s11252-009-0108-9
